// TEST: exec_methodinfer_box_map_call
// EXPECT: output "42;v21"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust, go
//
// Q-checker-method-generic-call-infer — infer a METHOD's OWN type parameter at
// a call site.
//
// `Box[T].map[U](f: Fn(T) -> U) -> Box[U]` introduces `U` as the method's own
// type parameter. The receiver pins the type's own param `T`; `U` must be
// inferred from the call ARGUMENT, exactly as a free function's type params are
// (the checker now freshens a method's own type-param names per call site
// instead of leaving them as a dangling `Named("U")`).
//
// Before the fix, the *declaration* of `map[U]` compiled (see
// go_method_generics_freefn_lowering.bock), but a *call* `b.map(dbl)` failed
// inference of `U` at check time on every target — which is why the type-zoo
// exerciser only declared `Box.map` and never called it. This fixture exercises
// the call on both inference shapes:
//
//   * `b.map(dbl)`    — `dbl: Fn(Int) -> Int`,    infers `U = Int`    → `Box[Int]`
//   * `b.map(to_str)` — `to_str: Fn(Int) -> String`, infers `U = String` → `Box[String]`
//
// so the result is verified end-to-end on all five targets (not just a clean
// compile). The second call confirms `U` is inferred to a type *distinct* from
// the receiver's pinned `T`.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

record Box[T] {
  value: T
}

impl Box {
  fn map[U](self, f: Fn(T) -> U) -> Box[U] {
    Box { value: f(self.value) }
  }
}

fn dbl(x: Int) -> Int {
  x * 2
}

fn to_str(x: Int) -> String {
  "v${x}"
}

fn main() -> Void {
  let b = Box { value: 21 }
  let doubled = b.map(dbl)
  let labelled = b.map(to_str)
  println("${doubled.value};${labelled.value}")
}
